  "text": "(i) Translational Attenuation -PERK Pathway. When mammalian cells are subjected to ER stress, the first and immediate response is translational attenuation in order to reduce the load of host protein synthesis in the ER and prevent the further accumulation of unfolded proteins [CITATION_1] . This is orchestrated by the type I ER transmembrane protein Protein kinaselike ER kinase (PERK), which represses global protein biosynthesis through the phosphorylation of translation initiation factor 2 (eIF2) on its alpha subunit (eIF2α). The lumenal domain of PERK is sequestered by Grp78 in unstressed cells at the ER membrane and its cytoplasmic domain is activated upon the release of Grp78 following ER stress.",
